                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d361">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.113 Senate Investigation/69: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-09-25T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 25, 1934—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>308. Your 429, September 25, 3 p.m. Please instruct Nanking to inform Political
                    Vice Minister for Foreign Affairs that Chinese Minister here has repeatedly
                    asked for this information, and that Department promptly took appropriate steps
                    to procure the information for confidential communication through the Minister
                    to the Ministry of Foreign Affairs. Peck<note n="41" xml:id="d361fn41">Counselor
                        of Legation in China; Consul General at Nanking.</note> should add that the
                    Senate Committee concerned is handling a huge amount of material and some delay
                    is unavoidable.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
